<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Public Law Solicitors Response to Consultation: Transforming legal aid: delivering a more credible and efficient system</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Public Law Solicitors (LAI 0079)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Public Law Solicitors</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public Law Solicitors has an acknowledged national reputation in its areas of specialism:  public law and community care. We have legal aid contracts in both fields. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.21pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These submissions concern the government’s proposal for reforming legal aid. We have add</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ressed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the proposal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to pay</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> practitioners only if permission is granted in judicial review claims, and the withdrawal of public funding from ‘borderline’ cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Payment of practitioners only if permission is granted in judicial review claims</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">constitutional importance of judicial review</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Judicial review is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not just</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> another type of litigation equivalent to any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">other. It has an absolutely vital</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> constitutional role in upholding the rule of law. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is the means by which a citizen may ask</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to adjudicate on the lawfulness of the actions (or inaction) of the state.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It prevents and remedies abuses </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of executive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> power.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any government that is considering reforms which have the potential for impacting on the accessibility of judicial review should do so with the utmost caution, with a clear understanding of the risks. It is not enough to ‘toll the bell of tight resources’.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  A careful and considered  enquiry needs to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undertaken which addresses fundamental questions about the consequences for the accountability of government  for the lawful exercise of its powers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those consequences </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> fall on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are so p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oor that they are eligible for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the financial assistance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the state to assist them with their legal costs, the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need for care and caution is that much greater</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Tho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se who will be affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposals  will be th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ose who are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">most vulnerable to the abu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se of state power because they are dependent on the decisions of the state for the very basic necessities of life  and do not have the resources (financial or otherwise)  to  resolve the problem themselves. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> There</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is absolutely no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sense that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">these proposals have been informed by any such careful and cautious consideration.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There has been no p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rior enquiry and recommendations by experts in the fiel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consulta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion period has been limited to 8 weeks, The impact assessment which accompanies th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e consultation proposals looks at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the impact on clients and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the impacts</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on providers, but does not  acknowledge any  implications for the most important issue for  us all: maintaining</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a proper check on th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> exercis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e of power by the state. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This policy is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">based on four assumptions, none of which are explored </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in detail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government’s proposals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and none of which, on examination, hold good. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Public funding is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">granted for a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> significant number o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f claims that are  so weak that  they should never have been p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ursued.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is possible for competent practitioners to make a more accurate assessment of the merits of the case – they simply need to be motivated to do so.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is financially sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for legal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> aid </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">practitioners to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> bear the inevitable losses that will b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e imposed by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scheme.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any increased costs will not outweigh the savings to be made.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Funding weak claims: is it a problem?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In his interview on the Today programme on 26 April, the Lord Chancellor said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“Well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> let me give you a raw piece of statistic that will explain the nature of the problem. In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2011,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the last year we had figures available, there were 11,359 applications for judicial review. In the end 144 were successful and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">all the rest of them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> tied up gove</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">rnment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">lawyers,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> local authority lawyers in time, in expense for a huge number of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cases of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> which virtually none were successful. We’re not saying that there shouldn’t be judicial review, we’re not saying that members of the public and organisations should n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ot be able to challenge public bodies, but what we are saying is that we have to raise the bar so that we have fewer cases that have no chance of succeeding.”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> [Emphasis added.]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In short</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the reason</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for this proposal is that it is believed that 98.5% of j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">udicial review cases are unmeritorious and proceedings should never have been issued. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> belief is clearly incorrect and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for this reason</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> alone this proposal should be withdrawn.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Maurice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sunkin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Professor of Public Law and Socio-Legal Studies , </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">University of Essex,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Varda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bondy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">director of Research at the Public Law Project </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have pu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">blished</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a paper which analyses the relevant figures </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in relation to civil non-immigration judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the material set out below summarises their analysis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir conclusions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reflect the reality which we experience as practitioners in the conduct of these cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Although 11359 cases were issued in 2011, there were permission decisions on only 6264 (55%).  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Maurice </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sunkin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Varda</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bondy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> say  that their resea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rch</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">found that a  significant proportion of cases withdraw at the post-issue but pre-permission stage because they, in some way, settled and, most significantly for the purpose of the  proposed reform, settled in the claimants’ favour. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bondy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sunki</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> conclude that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">49.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">% of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> civil non-immigration claims can be estimated to have been arguable at the permission stage. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> own figures suggest </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> figures are even better for publicly funded cases. At paragraphs 3.65-3.68 of the consultation pa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">per</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> information recorded for publicly funded cases is analysed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1799 funded</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cases “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">which did apply for permission”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 500 were refused permission with no benefit having been recorded to the client</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> i.e. 27% of the cases.  (The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recognises that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some have resulted in benefit to the client even though permission was ultimately refused</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because the public authority may have “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">modified its position” or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conceded in advance of the courts consideration.)  This suggests that in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 73% of cases permission was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">either granted or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> case </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ended </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">at this stage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with benefit to the client. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">What the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Government has not done</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undertake any analysis of overall   substantive success rates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sunkin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Bondy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> found </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of settlement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">grant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of permission (56%) and a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">claimant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">success rate at trial of 40%. If these rates were applied to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> figures for publicly funded ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ses (taking into account those where permission was refused but with benefit to the client)  a total of 1032  of the 179</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">9 cases where an application was made for permission  can be estimated to have been concluded successfully, a success rate of 57%. Elig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ibility for public funding requires prospects of success to be estimated at more than 50%.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In summary the statistical information available does not support the Lord Chancellor’s belief that 98.5% of judicial review cases in 2011 were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unmeritorious and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> should never have been brought.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> figures d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o not support the Government’s argument</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that there is a significant prob</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lem that needs to be addressed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and the problem</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> lies in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> flawed merits assessments by claimant lawyers using public funding. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In fact</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the figures s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uggest that claimants’ lawyers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are ‘getting it right’ more often than the meri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ts test actually requires. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Merits assessments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> seems to believe that Claimants’ lawy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘can do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">better’ in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">their initial merits assessments on the basis of which the application for public funding is made. They simpl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incentivised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to do so.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However there ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">absolutely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the factors which create difficulties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estimating prospects of success or any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">explanation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reasoning</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for concluding that improvement is possible.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Claimant’s legal team faces a number of difficulties </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">when estimating </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">prospects of success even at the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Variation in permission grant rates between judges</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The first of these </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the extent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to which the prospects of success are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">determin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> identity of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> judge dealing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ith</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> decisi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on. Research has demonstrated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">huge differentials in rate of g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rant between different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">judges</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Lack of precision in the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">arguability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">’ test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> A second factor (which may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">well be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> related to the first) is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the imprecision of the test applied by the courts at the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> stage. Recommendations for the introduction of a clear test in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the court rules ha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> been made by b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oth the Law </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Commission</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sir Jeffrey Bowman’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the Cro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">wn Office List</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2000</span><span style="font-family:Aria