t"> problem. Def</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorities,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> knowing that the claimant’s legal team will be taking</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the risk of bearing the costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of an unsuccessful claim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,  ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e less likely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to be willing to disclose informatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n which m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ay lead to a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more positive a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssessmen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of pro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pects of success.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In sh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cards are already stacked against the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimant’s legal team which is faced with a front-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">loaded procedure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. A judge must be persuaded there is an arguable case deserving of a full</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hearing right</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at the start, despi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">te the difficulties in accessing the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relevant information and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a very limited time period within which to investigate. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A sustainable risk for providers? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Legal aid practitioners are already paid at rates </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 9% lower than the rates payable nearly 20 years ago. This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">despite sig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ni</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">fi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cant increases in overheads of various kinds. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Legal aid practice is barely sustainable</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and there</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">margin in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> solicitors’ firms specialising in this work </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">either in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">profits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or cash</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> flow terms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to absorb </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">isk of  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">unremunerated </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is no evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk can be controlled by  more careful and considered merits assessments which would eliminate weak cases that should not be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">brought</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Not o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is there no evidence that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> generally  publ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c law special</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ists undertaking legal aid work  ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e making ill-considered judgment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">merits</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of their cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(see above)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, but the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re are many factors beyond their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ol inheren</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the nature of judic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proceedings which cr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ate a sign</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ifi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt risk  that  the case will end pre-permission without any concession of liability.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The risk they are being asked to bear is not only that a permission judge will disagree </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assessment of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arguability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as we understand it is not only to decline payment if permission is refused, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to decline payment unless permission is granted.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Pre-issue ‘settlement’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The risk of settlement after a full representation certificate has been granted is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particularly high in judicial review cases for a number of reasons each of which derives from the nature of judicial review itself.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">First, the tight time limits for issuing judicial review proceedings means that the Defendant as well as the Claimant has o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nly very limited time within which to consider the claim. Cases often settle on the brink of issuing once the majority of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">preparation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">costs have been incurred. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For the same reason the response to the letter before claim may not be provided </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14 day</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that the pre-action </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">protocol requires</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The public </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">certificate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> granted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but the response provides substantial new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">information whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h requires significant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an addendum letter before claim before issuing. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Defendant may only settle in response to that addendum letter. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> It is also not uncommon for the defendant to offer, immediately prior to issuing proceedings, to reconsider without conceding the underlying issue. It is appropriate to await the reconsidera</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion, but in the absence of a concession on the point at issue, it is not appropriate to bring the certificate funding to an end because the further decision may well prove to be flawed on the same basis.  This is a common scenario in community care </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> cases concerning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> decisions for individuals. The issue of concern in a judicial review might be the underlying policy such as the lawfulness of an eligibility policy, but, if the defendant authority offers to reassess, it may well be ina</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ppropriate to issue proceedings </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">because the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> reassessment may lead to a different </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">service–provision decision albeit without addressing the underlying policy issue. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Pre-permission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">settlement</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is not uncommon for judicial review proceedings to be br</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ought to an end pre-permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because of any concession the part of the defendant, but because they become ‘academic’ i.e. a ruling on the issue between the parties is no </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">longer of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any significance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to the claimant. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">because </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">udicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uniquely</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> - are concerned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not with an immutable historical incident which forms the subject matter of the case, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but often</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decision or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> inaction which may be overtaken by events in the course of the litigation. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  This is particularly prob</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lematic in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social welfare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> field, in particular community care,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where there is an ongoing relationship between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the public</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> authority and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e individual claimant. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> community care case challenge</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the lawfulness of a local authority’s policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on residential respite care for an adults with learning disabilities living in the family home wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h parents as the main carers. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">policy allocates</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> respite without re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">gard to the willingness of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">family carers to continue to provide care and the level r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">equired by the respite policy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and before permission is considered, the local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authority offers a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> supported living placement in a new development. The provision of respite care is no longer r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">elevant to that individual.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In other cases the actions of third parties may render the proceedings academic. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, a judicial review challenges the lawfulness of   </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> authority’s   eligibility policy. After proceedings are issued the local authority refers the claimant for an assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eligibility for NHS Continuing Healthcare which conclude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s/he is eligible and therefore no longer the responsibility of the l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ocal authority. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the express objective of this policy is to save money by reducing the number of unarguable cases being run and the mechanism for achieving this objective is to refuse to pay lawyers unless their case is granted permission.  H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">owever, this policy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will result in lawyers being refused payment for cases that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are perfectly arguable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  but which do not proceed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for reasons beyond their control.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It will also engender a litigious culture, hostile to settlement and compromise because the penalty for claimants’ lawyers for early settlement is non-payment for their work. This cannot be what is intended. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the lev</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l of the risk </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that lawyers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are being asked to undertake </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As pointed out above, judicial review proceedings are, in any event, front-loaded, and must be prepared </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> presented in sufficient detail to be in a position to satisfy a permission judge that the case sho</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uld proceed to full hearing. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But, in some case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, the costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">risk may</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> amount to considerably more than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the costs of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">preparing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> issue</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may order an oral permission hearing of its own volit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion, doubling the ‘normal’ costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. An </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erim relief may be required which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if contested</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y require a half day hearing, again doubling the costs of a paper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The court might order a rolled up hearing of its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">own </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">volition as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lternative to the gr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ant of interim relief</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> or in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">response</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">expedition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Claimant’s legal te</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">am would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in those circumstances</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be faced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with bearing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the full risk of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conducting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a case to trial which could involve costs </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the region of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£15</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">000 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to £20,000 an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in a complex case significantly more.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Pre-permission inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> costs</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Government</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> suggests that the  non-payment in pre-permission ‘settlement’ cases  and in cases where permission is refused but where there is benefit to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e client should not create difficulties for practitioners because  it is possible to secure an inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs order from the court. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This suggestion reveals a fundamental misunderstanding of the principles which currently govern the award </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of pre-permi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs in judicial review proceedings. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The principles to be applied </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the award of costs in  the Administrative Court were recently considered by the Court of Appeal in  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">M v Mayor and Burgesses of the London Borough of Croydon</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> [2012] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 595 8 May 2012.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">First of all the Court of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Appeal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> pointed out that  where litigation is compromised prior to trial the court is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not obliged to resolve a free-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">standing dispute about costs. (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">See </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 47</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here there has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> no tria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l or j</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">udgment the court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may not be in a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">position</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be able to do so. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">noted a “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sharp difference</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">” between  three different types of case (1) a case where a claimant has  been wholly successful whether following a contested hearing or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pursuant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to a set</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tlement (2)  a case where the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">claimant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has only succeeded in part </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">following</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">contested</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hearing or pursuant to a settlement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and (3) wher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been a compromise which does not actually reflect the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimant’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> claims (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 60).</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the first case the court commented it was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to see why the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">laimant should not recover all of his costs.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the second  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">type of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case the Master of the Rolls said:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">I would accept the argument that , where the parties have settled the claimant’s substantive claims on the basis that he succeeds only in  part there is often much to be said for concluding there is no order for costs….. In some such cases, it may help to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">consider who would have won if the matter had proceeded to trial …” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 62)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the third category of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">court </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is often </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">unable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to gauge whether ther</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">has been a successful party in any respect and, if</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> so, who it is.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">  However, in some such cases, i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t may well be sensible to look at the underlying claims and inquire whether it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> tolerably clear who would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">have won</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> if the matter had not settled.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">” (Para 63) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But the court stressed that the work involved must be proportionate to the amount of costs at s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">take. (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 77):</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“No order for co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ts will be the default order when the judge cannot without disproportionate expenditure of judicial time , if at all, fairly and sensibly make an order in favour of either party</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.” (Para 77)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Applying these principles to c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ases which are brought to an end without a substantive determination of their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arguability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at permission, then it soon becomes clear that th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposal would deprive the claimant’s legal team of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">payment for work properly done for reasons which have</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> nothing to do with the merits of the case</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> because inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs will not plug the funding gap. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">First of all where the case settles pre-issue of proceedings there is no mechanism for seeking an order for costs from the court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the defendant public authority refuses to pay costs which will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the case in the vast majority of cases.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secondly where cases become academic post–issue they will fall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> third category of case identified by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Court</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of Appea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> The court wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ll often not be in a position to gauge whether there is a successful party  without looking at whether it is tolerably clear that the Claimant would  have won had the matter not been brought to an end.  In a pre-permission case, the risk is that much great</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er that a court will find that the work involved in making such a determination at such an early stage in the case would involve disproportionate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">effort in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relation to the costs at stake. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lastly, in an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y event</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, these</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs principles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nsure that  pre-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sts are paid for arguable cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> where there has been no grant of permission by the court. The relevant consideration for  the court when determining the appropriateness of inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs is whether the Claimant would have s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ucceeded </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">at trial</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">whether the court would have granted permission.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> accepts that it is appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to fund pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">permission</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> work as long as permission is granted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(the case is arguable)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> even if the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">case is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unsuccessful at trial.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  But the proposals will result in non-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">payment in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> many cases which are perfectly arguable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">but where</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">court will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not award inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">costs pre</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">-permission because it is not satisfied that the case would have succeeded at trial. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">The consequences of ris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">k reduction behaviour by practitioners  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposed reform is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> more likely to ‘incentivise’ practitioners </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">either to withdraw from practice in this area </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">altogether or to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> decline to run cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not because they are unarguable but because they carry a higher risk. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The practices that most likely to withdraw from this field are specialist practices which do not have any means of covering </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">any losses</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> by cross-subsidising from other fields of work</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The types of case that will be most vulnerable to negative risk assessment decisions are those where the risk is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> higher </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for a number of reasons, for example: </span></li><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t is more </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">difficult </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to asse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ss merits because of the exten</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assessment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rel</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disclosure by the  defendant or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> involve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a novel point of law, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The case involves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">higher up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">front</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> prepa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tion costs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is a higher risk of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the case being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rendered academic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, such as in community care cases;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of risk is higher because of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he possibility of an oral permission or rol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed up hearing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ul></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; m