n style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> claimant’s lawyers to issue very quickly on grant of a certificate in order to avoid pre-issue settlements which will result in no payment for the work undertaken. Inevitably more judicial review claims will be issued as a result in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> order</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to achieve some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">possibility of securing either a permission decision or inter </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> costs. Again this will be at a cost to the Administrative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ourt.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">claimants are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> unable to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">secure repres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">entati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> there are more litigant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s in person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in consequence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. The courts themse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lves have recognised the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased costs to the court service of dealing with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> such cases.  In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">right v Michael Wright Supplies Ltd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> [2013] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 234,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> 2:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 45pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“It may be saving the Legal Services Commission which no longer offers legal aid for this k</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ind of litigation  but saving expenditure in one public department in this instance simply increases it in the courts. The expense of three judges of the Court of Appeal dealing with this kind of appeal is enormous. The consequences by way of delay  of oth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">er appeals which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">need to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> be heard are unquantifiable. The appeal would certainly never have occurred if the litigants had been represented.”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0