 style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">considered</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">projected saving to be derived for this particular proposal is only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£1million</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">it is certainly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bvious that there would be any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">net saving to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> at all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> if the consequential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">osts elsewhere in the system were taken into account. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The Government’s latest response </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In its recent consultation paper </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposals for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">further reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the Government intends to ameliorate some of the criticisms levelled at its original proposals by suggesting that payment in respect of legal aided judicial review claims in which permission is not granted may be made at the discretion of th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e Legal Aid Agency. This does not address the points made above which concern the detrimental effect </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on access to justice caused by placing the costs risk of judicial review claims on practitioners and/or claimants. The point being that in the majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">publically funded judicial reviews the risk of adverse costs awards will mean that legitimate claims cannot be pursued. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">27</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> September 2013 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#